Hi! :)

I looked up the "Column Selector Widget", seems to work pretty well...
Is there a way to use a link to select specific predefined columns to show/hide ?
I could use the selector dropdown menu but is there an easier way ?

I would like to have some fixed columns, and a link that I could use to show, say... columns 5 to 10, then another link to toggle columns 11 to 20, ...

![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/7962247/7253358/6f7cab26-e83c-11e4-8846-519d913614ba.png)

Here is an example using Slickgrid :

    $("#coverage").click(function () {
        var columns = [];
        columns = columns.concat(TVC.all, TVC.coverage);
        TVC.grid.setColumns(columns);
        $("#coltabs").find("li").removeClass("active");
        $(this).parent().addClass("active");
        setCheckAll();
    });

where TVC.all are the fixed columns and TVC.coverage the view specific ones.

Did I miss something in the documentation ?

I think I found an issue (or am not understanding your docuimentation) where multi-location updates is replacing ALL children under a node instead of replacing just the updated ones. 

IE: It's acting like set, and "setting" the parent node to the values listed.

Example database:
```
{
	"Parent": {
		"key1": node1,
		"key2": {
			"key01": node01,
			"key02": node02,
		}
		"key3": node3,
		"key4": node4
	}
}
```

If I attempt to use multi-location update to change the value of just Key1 and the Values under key02 using:

```
data = {
	"Parent/": {
		"key1": changedNode,
		"key2": {
			"key01": changedNode,
			"key02": changedNode
		}
	}
}
db.update(data)
```

It replaces all the values (IE< removing unchanged values). The end result would be:

```
{
	"Parent": {
		"key1": changedNode,
		"key2": {
			"key01": changedNode,
			"key02": changedNode,
		}
	}
}
```

Which is obviously not what I want. Could I be using this incorrectly? The linked blog post states that update will specifically not change the values that are not included in the update.

Using a password grant flow, along with the access and refresh token, I would like to return a User ID back to the client.
```
@views.route('/oauth/token', methods=['POST'])
@oauth.token_handler
def access_token(*args, **kwargs):
    return {
        'userID': 16
    }

```
There are no arguments passed to the function so I'm unsure as to how to check which User ID to pass through. If I had the Client ID or any of the tokens, I could do a check to find which user's it was. Would there be any method for doing this?

After reloading the page with stPersistent, the table is rendering from the localStorage. 

Everythings is well rendered except the scope value of stItemsByPage. 
The value is `stConfig.pagination.itemsByPage` (default:10) even if the table displays 50 lines. 

It makes my view displaying an incorrect value to the user. I tried to change this part of stPagination and it worked but I'm afraid to keep this since it breaks tests). 

``` javascript
link: function (scope, element, attrs, ctrl) {
        var defaultItemsByPage = ctrl.tableState().pagination.number ? +(ctrl.tableState().pagination.number) : stConfig.pagination.itemsByPage;
        scope.stItemsByPage = scope.stItemsByPage ? +(scope.stItemsByPage) : defaultItemsByPage;
        scope.stDisplayedPages = scope.stDisplayedPages ? +(scope.stDisplayedPages) : stConfig.pagination.displayedPages;
```

What would be a correct fix for this ? Thank you.

The --pass-pol flag appears to be missing the password complexity, it would be nice if this could be added.
### command syntax used
crackmapexec -u <username> -p <password> -d <domain> --pass-pol ip.addr

This should output the password complexity as well as the password policy, a good example is how enum4linux does it.

`$command = "rpcclient -W '$global_workgroup' -U'$global_username'\%'$global_password' '$global_target' -c \"getdompwinfo\" 2>&1";
        print "[V] Attempting to get Password Policy info with command: $command\n" if $verbose;
        $passpol_info = `$command`;
        chomp $passpol_info;
        print "\n";
        if (defined($passpol_info) and $passpol_info !~ /ACCESS_DENIED/) {
                print "[+] Retieved partial password policy with rpcclient:\n\n";
                if ($passpol_info =~ /password_properties: 0x[0-9a-fA-F]{7}0/) {
                        print "Password Complexity: Disabled\n";
                } elsif ($passpol_info =~ /password_properties: 0x[0-9a-fA-F]{7}1/) {
                        print "Password Complexity: Enabled\n";
                }
                if ($passpol_info =~ /min_password_length: (\d+)/) {
                        my $minlen = $1;
                        print "Minimum Password Length: $minlen\n";
                }
        } else {
                print "[E] Failed to get password policy with rpcclient\n";
        }
        print "\n";`

